_[Game of Thrones](/wiki/Game_of_Thrones "Game of Thrones")_ is an American
[fantasy](/wiki/Fantasy "Fantasy") [drama](/wiki/Television_drama "Television
drama") television series created by [David Benioff](/wiki/David_Benioff
"David Benioff") and [D. B. Weiss](/wiki/D._B._Weiss "D. B. Weiss"). The
series is based on the _[A Song of Ice and Fire](/wiki/A_Song_of_Ice_and_Fire
"A Song of Ice and Fire")_ novels by author [George R. R.
Martin](/wiki/George_R._R._Martin "George R. R. Martin"). The series takes
place on the fictional continents of [Westeros](/wiki/Westeros "Westeros") and
[Essos](/wiki/Essos "Essos") and chronicles the power struggles among noble
families as they fight for control of the [Iron
Throne](/wiki/Iron_Throne_\(A_Song_of_Ice_and_Fire\) "Iron Throne \(A Song of
Ice and Fire\)") of the Seven Kingdoms. The series starts when [House
Stark](/wiki/Characters_in_A_Song_of_Ice_and_Fire#House_Stark.2C_retainers.2C_and_bannermen
"Characters in A Song of Ice and Fire"), led by [Lord Eddard "Ned"
Stark](/wiki/Ned_Stark "Ned Stark") ([Sean Bean](/wiki/Sean_Bean "Sean Bean"))
is drawn into schemes against [King Robert Baratheon](/wiki/Robert_Baratheon
"Robert Baratheon") ([Mark Addy](/wiki/Mark_Addy "Mark Addy")) when the Hand
of the King [Jon Arryn](/wiki/Jon_Arryn "Jon Arryn") (Robert's chief advisor)
dies mysteriously.[1]

The series premiered on April 17, 2011, on [HBO](/wiki/HBO "HBO"). David
Benioff and D. B. Weiss both serve as executive producers along with [Carolyn
Strauss](/wiki/Carolyn_Strauss "Carolyn Strauss"), Frank Doelger, [Bernadette
Caulfield](/wiki/Bernadette_Caulfield "Bernadette Caulfield") and George R. R.
Martin.[2][3] Filming for the series has taken place in a number of locations,
including Croatia, Northern Ireland, Iceland and Spain.[4][5][6] Episodes are
broadcast on Sunday at 9:00 pm Eastern Time,[7][8] and the episodes are
between 50 and 81 minutes in length.[9] The first six seasons are available on
DVD and [Blu-ray](/wiki/Blu-ray "Blu-ray").

The series was renewed for a seventh season in April 2016,[10] which premiered
on July 16, 2017 and consisted of seven episodes.[11] The series will conclude
with its eighth season, which will consist of six episodes.[12][13] As of
August 27,
2017,[[update]](//en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=List_of_Game_of_Thrones_episodes&action=edit)
67 episodes of _Game of Thrones_ have aired, concluding the seventh season.
The show's episodes have won numerous
[awards](/wiki/List_of_awards_and_nominations_received_by_Game_of_Thrones
"List of awards and nominations received by Game of Thrones") including two
[Primetime Emmy Award for Outstanding Drama
Series](/wiki/Primetime_Emmy_Award_for_Outstanding_Drama_Series "Primetime
Emmy Award for Outstanding Drama Series").[3]
